The '''Differential Doppler effect''' occurs when light is emitted from a rotating source.
In [[Circumstellar dust|circumstellar]] environments it describes the difference in photons arriving at orbiting dust particles. Photons that originate from the limb that is rotating away from the particle are [[Redshift|red-shifted]], while photons emitted from the limb rotating toward the particle are [[Blueshift|blue-shifted]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=McDonough |first=T. R. |year=1975 |title=Effects of Stellar Spin and Diameter on the Poynting-Robertson Effect |journal=News Lett. of the Astronomical Society of New York |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=32 |doi= }}</ref>
